          <h2>Who Miao He Serves in London Ontario</h2>
          <p>London's Chinese-Canadian community includes both long-established families and a large population of students and recent graduates connected to Western University. The family law needs of these groups overlap — but each has specific considerations.</p>

          <h3>Western University Students and Graduates: Divorce Across Immigration Status</h3>
          <p>Western University draws thousands of Chinese students annually. Some marry during their studies — to fellow students, to partners from home, or to Canadian citizens — and face divorce before or after graduation. The key facts to know: if either spouse has been ordinarily resident in Canada for one year or more, Ontario courts have jurisdiction to grant the divorce. A study permit does not prevent you from divorcing. Miao He has specific experience advising clients on how immigration status intersects with the divorce process — and when to also consult an immigration lawyer about the downstream effects.</p>

            <h3>Visa and Immigration Status: Flagging the Issues Early</h3>
          <p>One issue that London clients sometimes overlook is the immigration consequence of divorce for the other spouse. If your spouse holds a spousal open work permit, is in the middle of a sponsored PR application, or holds any immigration status derived from your relationship, the divorce may affect their status. This is an immigration law question — not a family law question — but Miao He flags it early so clients can seek the right advice before filing. Getting the sequencing right matters.</p>

          <h3>Divorce and Property Division for London Families</h3>
          <p>London's property market has grown significantly. Regardless of location, Ontario's Net Family Property Equalization rules apply: the increase in value during the marriage is divided, while pre-marital value, gifts, and inheritances may be excluded. Miao He advises London clients on accurate valuation, proper exclusions, and full financial disclosure — by Zoom for most of the process, with court appearances handled in London when necessary.</p>

          <h3>Child Custody: Cultural Arrangements in London</h3>
          <p>Chinese-Canadian families in London face the same cultural custody considerations as elsewhere — Chinese-language schooling, grandparent involvement, travel to China. Miao He builds Parenting Plans that address these specifics in legally binding terms, reducing future disputes by being precise about each party's rights and obligations.</p>

